deck_excerpt: Synchro summon the best synchro monsters (Nov, 2023)
deck_description: This deck is incredibly powerful. The deck grants the abiltiy to summon all four level 12 dragon synchro monsters in one turn. The deck is centered around stardust, synchron, and junk cards, which allows you to synchro summon junk speeder. You will then be able to go on to summon crimson dragon and a level 12 dragon synchro monsters. Typically you can summon crimson dragon multiple times in one turn, allowing you to summon three level 12 dragon synchro monsters (and cosmic quasar dragon can summon the last level 12 dragon synchro). Crimson dragon is great in this deck because it also acts as a searcher, enhancing your plays even further. The deck provides outstanding draw power, negation, attack power, and search ability. One of my favorite decks of all time. - Created by dg

Pure Galaxy-Eyes Deck (Post October 2019 Banlist)

 

This updated Galaxy-Eyes deck is mainly for bringing out Xyz monsters, such as Galaxy-Eyes Photon lord and Cyber Dragon Infinity, which can negate and distrupt your opponents turn.


The Deck:

 

  • Main Deck(Monsters) -

    • Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon(x3)

      • This card is at 3 as you want to see it in your hand to combo with Galaxy soldier in your hand. You also want to see it as it can battle monsters that cant be destroyed by battle, by instead banishing them for the phase.



  • Galaxy Knight(x2)

    • This is at 2 because you dont want to see it in your hand as much due to it being a brick. You want to search this card from the effect of Galaxy Soldier (you should discard Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon for the effect of Galaxy Soldier). This card does take up a normal summon from you but in return can summon another level 8 for you to go into your XYZ monsters.



  • Galaxy Soldier(x3)

    • One of the best cards in the main deck as it allows you discard a card to special summon itself and search a "Galaxy" monster. This card will generally be summoned by discarding Galaxy-Eyes Photon dragon to search Galaxy Knight, assuming that you have not normal summoned prior to Galaxy Soldiers special summon. Having more than 2 Galaxy Soldiers can also result in you summoning Cyber Dragon Infinity.



  • Galaxy Wizard(x3)

    • This card is your main normal summon and a great card for searching and setting up. This card can also turn into a level 8 thus helping you with your XYZ summons. Futhermore if able to summon this card, with Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon in the GY and Photon Vanisher or and other body on the field, then you can tribute Galaxy Wizard and search Galaxy Trance which you can make Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon with Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord. On your opponents turn you can search Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon via Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lords second effect. This gives you two distruptions on the field and and other such as Tachyon Transmigration.



  • Photon Orbital(x3)

    • Now we get into cards which are mainly used for utility. This card just gives a free search which this deck likes. This card can also be used as Galaxy Soldier's discarder or Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon's discarder.



  • Photon Vanisher(x3)

    • This card allows the deck to basically get a free Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon in your hand. This helps alot and can even be used to special summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon or Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon. This card can be used as discard material.




 

  • Main Deck(Spells) -

    • Accellight(x1)

      • Acts as the 4th copy of Galaxy wizard and shall only be used for the purpose. (That's how good Galaxy Wizard is in this deck).



  • Galaxy Expedition(x3)

    • This card Extends your plays and I just cant see why you wont run 3 of this. This card and Galaxy Wizard is a free Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord.



  • Galaxy Trance(x2)

    • This card is EXTREMELY GOOD but we only run two because it's a card you want to search off Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord as a way to get an XYZ monster after your opponent destroys all your cards (if they do). The card can also be bricky as you may have no way to send Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon to the GY.



  • Monster reborn(x1)

    • Extender.



  • Photon Sanctuary(x3)

    • A free Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon, allowing you to summon more XYZ monsters from the Extra Deck



  • Return Of The Dragon Lords(x3)

    • A better monster reborn as it protects your Link and XYZ monsters



  • Trade-In(x3)

    • Pot of Greed is banned and this card allows you to get your Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon from your hand to the GY. If you bricked and you have Trade-In, Photon Vanisher and a card you can normal summon, it will make you refresh your hand with some bodies on the field.



  • Galaxy Zero(x1)

    • You can summon XYZ monsters for free and the XYZ summon using them and bypass Galaxy Zero's effect or this card can be used to extend. This card is not searched usually and you want it late game.



  • Called By The Grave(x3)

    • Your deck does search and can be irritated by hand traps. But you can still play on even if your opponent has a hand trap. This card is just here for extra backup and support. It can also be used to distrupt your opponent on their turn.




 

  • Main Deck(Traps) -

    • Tachyon Transmigration(x3)

      • A negate dedicated for Galaxy-Eyes, why not run 3?




 

  • Extra Deck

    • Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon(x1)

      • This card destroys a card and can summon a Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon. So summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon (Effect: Steal a monster from your opponent) >> XYZ summon into Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon (Effect: Destroy a monster) >> XYZ summon into Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon (Effect: Destroy a card). But you cant attack.



  • Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon(x1)

    • Good for XYZ summoning better XYZ monsters and can control the field with its effect.



  • Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon(x1)

    • Good for destroying monsters... also has 4000 ATK



  • Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon(x1)

    • A great card for battle negation and for Tachyon Tansmigration.



  • Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon(x1)

    • This card can gain big attack for OTKs.



  • Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord(x2)

    • The card you'll summon the most. This card is a negation and a searcher. You must run 2 minimum.



  • Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy(x1)

    • This card can make it the focus of attacks and negate spell cards which are used a lot in decks.



  • Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand(x1)

    • Great for protection or negation



  • Thunder End Dragon(x1)

    • This card should be a card of your choice. Maybe a Rank 4 or a Link monster (Borrelsword)



  • Number 97: Draglubion(x1)

    • Unless you've been restricted by card effects which have stated that you cannot summon other monsters except light monsters, this card is great as with its effect you can summon Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon and used its effect to have 7200 ATK for OTKs. (This card replaced Galaxy-Eyes Dark Matter Dragon. RIP Dark Matter, your fellow Galaxy-Eyes XYZ monsters missing you)



  • Cyber Dragon Nova(x1)

    • To summon Cyber Dragon Infinity



  • Cyber Dragon Infinity(x1)

    • A great negation on the field.



  • Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon(x2)

    • This is your Link card and you'll be summoning this card the most as well to get more XYZ monsters on the field. Its summoning effect allows you to get back a card which it mainly would be (in order of piority):

      1. Galaxy Solider (for Cyber Dragon Infinity)

      1. Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon(For its own effect). (This can also be 1st place just depends on the situation)

      1. Photon Orbital (if used as material for the Link summon or sent to the GY as a discarder) so you can use its search effect

      1. Any Photon or Galaxy monster for (its own effect again)






 

  • Side Deck

    • Personally, I think you should make it yourself. Not because im lazy. Look above, I did all of that typing for you. But I think the side deck should be up to the player to choose from.


 


The deck master is Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord as its the card which you summon the most as it is a negation and a searcher.

Note: This should be taken as a guide and you should play how you want to play this deck and make changes. I personally think this is the peak at which this deck and go if playing in the current meta.

Your goal is to summon King of the skull servant. First of all, it's highly recommended to send as many skull servants as possibile to the graveyard, in order to increase King's attack. Your first strategy consists into sending wightprice from your hand/deck to the graveyard: use Gozuki's effect or card trooper's effect. In this way, you'll be able to activate wightprince's effect, and send a skull servant and a lady in wight from the deck/hand to the graveyard. The cheerful coffin is another useful card because allows you to send monster from you hand to the graveyard.

Once wightprince, skull servant and the lady in wight have been sent to the graveyard, you can activate wightprince's effect: banish all these 3 monsters and special summon the king from your deck. Now you can activate burial from another dimension to bring back your 3 monsters and boost the king's attack.

Wall of light and gravity bind are useful cards to control the field and to give you the time to set your board with 1/2 kings with 3k/4k atk points each. Extra deck is not necessary, but this deck can easily spam monsters even thanks to zombie master, and borreload dragon is quite strong.
Your main card are Vampire Retainer and Vampire Familiar, they allow you to cicle through your deck pretty easily and find the pieces to your combos.

This is a defense deck; use the powerful effect of the monsters which can be special summoned form the hand to stop every opponent's moves, then use "Dark/"Quaking Mirror Force" to destroy every chance of victory... if you want to have fun with the deck, try to use "Ghostrick-Skeleton" to destroy opponent's deck with its almost infinite effect.

This is a dedicated going-second deck that revolves around utilizing cards such as Super Polymerization, in order to wipe the board while summoning powerful Fusion monsters.

Hi, Grayewick the Fusion strategy enjoyer here, back with an EDOPro AI classic, Mathmechs. Yes, I blind second. Yes, this isn't a cheap deck to build. Yes, I do not play Pot of Desires because everyone's playing Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. Yes, I literally do not care about getting Maxx "C"-ed because your opponent won't have another turn to play as soon as either Avramax or Final Sigma hits the board. As per usual, cards on the main are the cards that I would personally play and the tech options will be placed in the side.

"So, how does this deck exactly work?"

In summation: One Punch.

First of all, let me address this one thing: If not for literally Parallel eXceed and even with Mathmech Diameter honestly, this deck would be slow as fuck. I'd be running Double Summons like I'm playing a slower version of Powerload Ogre turbo and yes, it does brick, that's why we blind second to get that extra card, and you'll never know if your opponent is playing a blind second strategy as well, and if they do, they probably run Kaijus, which kills all your boss monsters. So deck strategy, it's pretty straightforward. Make either Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax, Accesscode Talker, Borrelsword Dragon, or the archetypal boss monster Geomathmech Final Sigma and one shot your opponent with big number. That's why we also run Forbidden Droplet and Evenly Matched, because we want to end games as soon as possible, and it would be stupid for your opponent to leave a back row without a monster on the field, unless it's an Eldlich player that hard drew Skill Drain.

So yeah, if you want to be extra annoying, use Skill Drain as well after summoning Geomathmech Final Sigma and trigger your opponent's PTSD from Apoqliphort Towers turbo because fuck it, it's basically the same thing, except Towers messes up with your opponent's resources and makes them feel violated while Final Sigma messes up with your opponent's LP and pride after getting one shot by a deck that's not even rogue. Have fun in the ladder.

Oh, Tiger is at 3 in Master Duel? Don't mind if I do...

The strategy is simple-beat over your opponent by dancing their butts off (Leo Dancer+a link boss monster or another copy of itself. Preferably with Chick banished for no battle phase shenanigans.)

Core Ratios:

Main Deck 

3)

Tiger because soft One Per Turn clauses are easily subverted by bouncing. Also a Daruma Dolltarget for backrow popping/revivial

Marten because you can bounce Tiger and get more fusion/link material through its revival(or go into Tiger King)

Kaldeo Chick because 1)dumping for cost means negates don't affect the dumping, 2)you can cheat our your fusions with the name change, 3)battle protection means no 3500 damage to you via Magic Cylinder, and 4)Polymerizationrecycling. Also level 4 for Tiger King.

Lunalight Fusion, despite being a Hard Once Per Turn, means you can get Leo Dancer out with two Lunalight Monsters in hand and an Extra Deck on the opp's field. Also searchable by Marten.

Luna Light Perfume (which, do note, is NOT searchable by Marten because of that extra space in "Luna Light") is archetypal Revival and Deck searching, not Once Per Turn. Need I say more?

2)

White Rabbit is nice revival and backrow bouncing, but having the revival on normal summon is rough due to Chick usually being a better call.

Emerald Bird is nice recovery, helps un-brick hands and get other Lunalights into grave and yet another Tiger King material...but Chick is still a better normal summon, and the discard can be a bit awkward.

Black Sheep...honestly could be at 3, since it pays for itself through both of its effects, but I find that it being in your opening hand with no other lunalights in hand can be rough.

Allure of Darkness because you run a lot of Darks, but you do have the occasional Light monster. I can see this at 3 if you can take the risk.

1)

Tenki honestly could also be at 3 since it is an amazing searcher, but usually 1 does the job enough for me. More room for handtraps.

Foolish Burial Goods could also be at three since it gets Perfume and Serenade Dance into grave, but as one who doesn't run Pots, hand space can be tight.

Purple Butterfly is nice attack boosting and gets Lunalights out of  your hand, but I would rather see it more in grave than in hand.

Blue Cat because you only need one for the atk boost and sadly Mystic Tomato strats in this day and age aren't nearly as viable with all the negates and banishing.

Crimson Fox is nice targeting protection and atk dropping which is good for early setup or baiting, but your Big Boss Fusions all have some protection and you have other ways of boosting attack.

Polymerization/Fusion Substitute since you can recover both via Chick...but you also haveLunalight Fusion.

Serenade Dance is something you want to see in grave far more than in hand for the revival effect, but at least is a target for Martin in a pinch and an extra card for White Rabbit bouncing (remember, Lunalight cards, not just Monsters).

Revolt because it is a nice way to recover your banished monsters...but you probably have your other Tri-Brigade links in the grave barring Shuraig, so having more than one can be dead draws.

 

Extra Deck

2)

All fusions but Cat Dancer-Two Leo Dancers are more than enough to OTK, Two Saber Dancers to have one on field and one for the attack boost, Two Panther Dancers in case they banish your first from the grave.

1)

Cat Dancer mostly because you'll be dumping Panther Dancer through Chick instead. Is a nice first turn option if you can't get to Leo Dancer, though.

Tri-Brigade links are pretty much to get a banish off the field or to link climb into your other archetypal boss monsters.

Daruma Doll is nice backrow removal and helps link climb.

Top 5 Costa Rica Regional AGOV 2023

I like how the deck works today, i don´t use S:P Little Knight cause i haven´t but it yet so i used Azalea and works nice :D
Magicians, Warlocks, and Sorcerers are yours to command with the "Spellcaster’s Judgment" Structure Deck. Use your Spell Cards to strengthen your monsters and damage your opponents.
Mannadium Deck List

Qliphorts

Qliphorts are a bit of an oddity in that they hate being Pendulum Summoned. The main reason to Pendulum Summon most of the Qliphorts are just to use them as Tribute fodder for other Qliphorts. Regardless, Qliphorts aren't as strong as they used to be, but they can end up doing some really neat stuff thanks to how great of a searcher Qliphort Scout is, and how searchable it is thanks to Summoner's Art. You can then use Wavering Eyes to destroy Scout and 1 other Qliphort in the scale, search another Scout, and search again.

  • Going into Qliphort Genius is nigh-mandatory, so to help with that, this decklist runs a small Infinitrack engine that also helps trigger the on-Tribute effect of some of the Qliphorts.
  • This build also runs Armory Call, mainly because it can either get you access to Saqlifice... or let you drop Apoqliphort Towers on your opponent's turn via Supermagic Sword of Raptinus, which never gets old.

deck_name: Centurion / RA01 cheap staples / Crossout package
deck_description:
Centurion engine re-work using more budget staples (many from RA01) rather than 'Chaos Angel' and 2/3 'Triple Tactics Talent' (these cards are obviously preferred but $$$)

 

due to centurions engine size currently we have to make do with cards that are helpful / supportive. One of the no brainers of course has been to run a small bystial package alongside 2-3 Kashtira Fenrir, these are easy bodies to get on the field, who both have some great follow up effects. Running level 6 bystials and level 7 fenrirs will help give you access to level 10 and level 11 synchro plays by still using the main engine's tuner. You wont have to give up your precious ash blossom negate for access to a level 11. :)

 

I am interested to see how the horus cards play along this deck as well. Another package that is relatively small that could work is the ken/gen support package. I think it would really shine here with the overall size and compromise of Centurion currently. 

Centurion is poised to be stronger and more consistent by about spring of next year we shoul all be looking at a few more centuirion cards :)

deck_excerpt: This is my main deck in Yu-Gi-Oh! Master Duel, feel free to use.
deck_description:
This deck is pretty straight forward, and is my first... "Meta" kind of deck. It's probably not the greatest Swordsoul deck ever, but it's been pretty solid for me.

The default strategy of this deck, is starting with "Swordsoul of Mo Ye" summoning a token, Synchro into "Swordsoul Grandmaster - Chixiao", using the effect of "Swordsoul Grandmaster - Chixiao", and "Swordsoul of Mo Ye" in the graveyard to bring "Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan", special summon "Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan" by sending 1 "Swordsoul" or "Wyrm" monster from your hand to the graveyard, special summon a token, then Synchro in to "Baronne de Fluer", + Effect of "Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan" in the gy to inflict 1600 damage.

That's just 1 idea anyway.

Feel free to use this deck, and if you have any recommendations to improve upon my build, please let me know.

deck_excerpt: The title of this decklist sounds like a pop brand flavour XD. Nuke your opponent and OTK with Spright!
deck_description:
This deck is inspired by recent YCS tops that featured a very interesting way to play Spright - the deck is stuffed full of blind second boardbreaker spells. 
 
After the board and gamestate is simplified with the power spells, Spright can easily OTK by generating a lot of level 2/link 2/rank 2 bodies on field and powering them up with the powerful SPRIGHT GAMMA BURST!

This quick play spell (playable during the damage step so it 's very hard to negate) boosts every level 2/link 2/rank 2 monster on the field by 1400ATK/DEF easily enabling your Spright monsters to OTK!

Since this deck is relatively easy to pilot (standard Spright combo) with a very easy gameplan (blow stuff up with boardbreakers) there won't be an in-depth guide this time. Spright Gamme Burst is the perfect deck to ladder up and grind with in Masterduel since games tend to be quick, straight forward and easy to play. Give it a shot, you'll be pleasantly surprised! 
 
GLHF Duelists! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Brice Dodeller

Tournament: Créteil WCQ Regional – November 11th 2023

Placement: 1st Place

This is a rehash of Clown Control for Edison Format. 

What's Clown Control? Well it's using a mix of Dream Clown/Crass Clown to consistently bounce/destroy monsters via their effects, establishing formidable field presence with relatively little need to reuse resources with the correct stalling tech in place. It's a deck used aplenty in older formats, but nothing really exists post-Goat for what a Clown Control deck could look like so I figured I'd try to see if it was feasible.

......kinda? 

Like don't get me wrong this isn't meta in the slightest, but I was pretty shocked by how well this plays against certain decks that struggle against consistant removal/disruption. Slower Edison decks huff and puff a lot against the pace that this establishes and I've generally gotten good starting hands to make sure that pressure comes really early. Lightsworn players also generally couldn't really handle the deck either, though that's likely for reasons relating to how the deck is made.

The main monsters are

Dream Clown 

Crass Clown 

Blade Rabbit 

These are the core of the strat; you want these active as soon as possible. 

To assist with this, we also use a bunch of alternative tech options, namely ways to get the monsters on the field (Nimble, for instance, can get Rabbit from deck) or ways to stall/draw. This isn't too much of a issue given the immense backrow backing these up most of the time.

Goblin Attack Force is the beater of the deck. Generally it wouldn't be even worth sniffing at due to the general state of Edison being way too fast for a 2300 beatstick with a long cooldown after one attack, but with the stalling and the battle position changes? It becomes a lot more useful in bashing away bigger monsters.

Gale is only in here for a Tuner option that's actually half-worth using here. Couldn't really find one that was more appropriate. 

Generally what saves Clown Control is the backrow; stuff like Stumbling, Level Limit, Labyrinth, etc. These allow for the Control side of the deck to shine by frequently slowing down the game or allowing your main monsters to destroy more easily. You need more than that in Edison so we also throw in 3x Book of Moon (combos well with Nimble/Riko to boot) Royal Oppression and a bunch of other cards to keep either disrupting or defending to keep the core altogether. 

Dimensional Fissure  is super strong for this format as well; unlike in Goat there's not really any reliable way to get back monsters banished back very easily. You either have to have be playing very specific cards that many conventional decks don't use (like D.D.R. or Burial, both are clunky though and you usually use them just to extend combos anyway) or play through that instead; something many decks in Edison can't really do given how valuable the Graveyard is to their playstyle. 

Can the deck win matches? Definitely, I've piloted it to those on ladder and otherwise. It's jank, but it's jank that can win matches if it starts well so it's better than average jank in my mind. Could've thrown in some recruiters like with prior builds (which had things like Mystic Tomato, Rat, etc) but there's so much non-battle effects being thrown around that it's really just not worth the trouble lol

deck_excerpt: I will do ANYTHING for a Level 9
deck_description:
There's this funny little card called Full Active Duplex which is a Level 9 WIND Cyberse Monster. Unless you want me to invent a line that involves Ritual Summoning Paladin of Storm Dragon and using its effect to Tribute itself to Special Summon a Level 5 or higher Cyberse monster from hand or Deck, I am just going to go through some Code Talker lines to search for Cynet Codec which will search me a WIND Cyberse Monster from Deck when I Link Summon Excode Talker. Duplex can be Specialed from hand by banishing 2 Link Monsters from GY which is not a hard condition to fulfill, but it is actually just the act of searching it out and having a consistent way of getting Links into GY that you need to get over first. And what better way to do all of that than to play a Code Talker engine. Sadly, because we aren't playing enough Code Talkers in Extra, we can't really make much use out of playing things like Code Exporter, Code Radiator, and Code Generator, and since we can't play any cards that Cyberse-lock us, we can't play some really really good cards like Firewall Defenser (which means we also can't play Firewall Phantom) and Transcode Talker. However, it is pretty easy to actually get to both Codec and Excode Talker, but it is just a matter of fact whether or not you actually draw World Legacy Monstrosity. We technically do have the capability of making Mekk-Knight of the Morning Star to search for it from Deck, but we don't actually play any other World Legacy cards or Mekk-Knight monsters to discard for its effect. This Deck ends on either Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax or Firewall Dragon Darkfluid - Neo Tempest Terahertz (with Cyberse Desavewurm in GY and the ability to send Mereologic Aggregator from Extra to GY on your opponent's turn) in addition to your Prediction Princess plays. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, and 3 Prediction Bibliomuse. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned through Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On Flip she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and as a Quick Effect, she can flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip 1 monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down if she is Tributed and sent to the GY, and when she is flipped face-up, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand. And while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated monster effects of all monsters on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up, and if it is destroyed from field, you can add a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. 1 Full Active Duplex which you can Special Summon from hand by banishing 2 Link Monsters from your GY and if it is sent to GY, you can give a Cyberse monster you control 1000 ATK. 3 Parallel eXceed which you can Special Summon from hand to a zone a Link Monster points to when you Link Summon, and if it is Normal or Special Summoned, you can Special Summon another Parallel eXceed from Deck. And whenever Parallel eXceed is Special Summoned by the effect of a Parallel eXceed, it’s Level becomes 4 which is not really relevant in this Deck as we are just going to be using it as Link Material either way. 1 Balancer Lord which you can pay 1000 Life Points once per turn to have an extra Normal Summon of a Cyberse Monster and its other effect allows you to Special Summon a Level 4 or lower monster from hand if it is banished, but I don’t see how you can accomplish that in this Deck. This is more of less sort of the 40th card I decided to slot into this Deck. It basically acts as a way to get more monsters on board for Link plays which is pretty good in and of itself, but I feel like you are in more situations where you don’t have a Cyberse that you can just outright Normal Summon from your hand considering that you only play 9 theoretical Normal Summons and the rest of your Deck is high-level monsters and Spells. 3 Firewall Guardian. This card can Special Summon itself back from the GY if it was used as material for the Link Summon of a Cyberse monster. Even though this card goes crazy with Firewall Defenser, we sadly can’t play Defenser because it Cyberse locks you in general and not just from the Extra Deck. If you are Cyberse-locked from the Extra Deck, we can work with that since the only necessary monster we need for our Prediction Princess plays from our Extra Deck is Mereologic Aggregator which is a Cyberse monster. 3 Formud Skipper. This card can a Link Monster in your Extra Deck to have itself be treated as the same name, Type, and Attribute as that monster for a Link Summon this turn. But the effect that we are actually using in this Deck is it adding a Level 5 or higher Cyberse monster from Deck to hand if it is used as Link Material and sent to the GY. This can get us either Parallel eXceed or Duplex, but I say that you should search for eXceed rather than Duplex because Formud is usually going to be your Normal Summon and your Link-1 monsters don’t really give ways to extend your plays, so you can’t really get 2 Links into grave to Summon Duplex. However, eXceed can get you more material to do just that. 3 Micro Coder which can be used as Link Material from the hand if you are using a Cyberse monster you control as Link Material for a Code Talker monster. And if it is used as Link Material for the Summon of a Code Talker monster and sent to GY from hand or field, you can add a Cynet Spell/Trap from Deck or add a Level 4 Cyberse monster instead if it was on field. You are always going to be using Coder to search a Cynet Spell/Trap in order to get access to Cynet Codec to get our searches going. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Cynet Mining which discards a card to search a Level 4 or lower Cyberse Monster from Deck. This gets you Firewall Guardian, Formud Skipper, Micro Coder, or even Balancer Lord, whatever you need as a starter or extender. And since it does discard a card for cost, you can discard either Tarotrei or Tarotreith since you can Ritual Summon them from GY with Underworld Ritual. 3 Cynet Codec. This card is the focal point of Code Talker, translating to becoming the focal point of this Deck as well. Once per chain, if a Code Talker monster is Special Summoned from the Extra Deck to your field, you can target that monster and add a Cyberse monster with the same Attribute as that monster from your Deck to your hand, but you are Cyberse-locked from the Extra Deck and cannot add a Cyberse monster with that Attribute for the rest of this turn with this effect. There are 2 main cards that we are focusing on searching with this card. If you hard draw this card, you can search for Micro Coder if you Link Summon Code Talker, and if you search this card at some point in your combo, you can search for Full Active Duplex from Deck if you Link Summon Excode Talker. I feel like Code Talkers along with Cynet Codec are the best way to search for Duplex and have enough Link Monsters in GY to actually Special Summon Duplex from hand. If it weren’t for that I’d have already given up on making a Prediction Princess Deck work with Duplex. Next up, 1 Cynet Optimization. It essentially gives you an Extra Normal Summon of a Cyberse monster during your Main Phase at the cost of restricting you to only Special Summoning Cyberse monster from Extra Deck. Again, we are completely fine with being Cyberse-locked from the Extra Deck in this Deck, so we have the ability to utilize cards like these without facing any repercussions. We only need 1 copy because you either hard draw it or you search it in a situation where you already have access to Codec. The extra Normal Summon gives you good ways to extend, especially since we can’t play most of the good Cyberse monsters that get material really easily onto the board as they Cyberse lock you in general and not just from the Extra Deck. 1 Instant Fusion which gets you to Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9’s from Deck with a different Type and Attribute than it with different names. And finally, 3 Pot of Prosperity. 

Extra Deck: 1 Cyberse Desavewurm which can be banished from your field or GY when your opponent activates a Spell/Trap card or effect while you control a Link-4 or higher Cyberse monster to negate that activation. You send this off of Terahertz on your turn to have a negate ready for your opponent’s turn, especially against something like a board clearing Spell/Trap. 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. And since Code Talker is generic, you can actually use it as Link Material or as an extender for Link plays. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck when sent to GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon and it can target any number of monsters in Gy up to the number of its materials, detach the same number of materials, and attach those monsters from GY. This allows you to recycle Herald for more searches. However, you actually get to use its last effect in this Deck. If it is sent to GY, you can target a face-up card on field and negate its effects until the end of the turn. You send Desavewurm to GY with Terahertz on your turn to have a negate live and send this on your opponent’s turn with Terahertz as it is a Quick Effect to negate a face-up card your opponent controls. Speaking of, 1 Firewall Dragon Darkfluid - Neo Tempest Terahertz which requires 3 or more Cyberse monsters as Material which is fairly easy to do considering how easily you can Link climb while retaining material on board in this Deck (Ex: Excode Talker + Link Decoder + Mereologic Aggregator). It negates monster effects activated by your opponent during the Battle Phase and it can Quick Effect send a Cyberse monster from Deck or Extra Deck to GY to gain that monster’s Attribute and gain 2500 ATK. And it can attack monsters a number of times equal to its different Attributes. 1 Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax which is untargetable and forces your opponent’s monsters to only be able to attack it, and it gains the ATK of your opponent’s Special Summoned monster it battles, and if it’s Link Summoned and sent to GY by your opponent, you can spin a card on field. 1 Accesscode Talker. 1 Excode Talker which really serves no purpose in this Deck other than being a WIND Code Talker monster to search a WIND Cyberse monster off of Codec. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Code Talker which is just a generic Link-2 Cyberse monster and a Code Talker in name. 1 Code Talker Inverted which can Special Summon a Cyberse monster from hand to a Zone it points to on Link Summon. And 2 Link Decoder which can Special Summon itself from GY if it is sent there as material for a Cyberse Link Monster with 2300 or more original ATK, banishing itself when it leaves field. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Triple Tactics Talents, 3 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 1 Evenly Matched.

deck_description: Just a deck idea

Upon special requests to make this deck, I have been testing Abyss Actors from scratch and this deck is very casual but can go up against tier two decks without losing. I normally do not upload OCG based decks or decks with OCG cards in them since I live in the USA and want to stick to the current meta game we have in the TCG. I have found this Pure Abyss Actor deck to be fun to play and there are many combos hidden within the deck to be discovered for people who are trying this specific deck for the first time. The combos involve the Abyss Actor cards themselves and the extra deck monsters, especially Heavymetalfoes Electrumite. This deck utilizes all of the Abyss Actor monsters and the Abyss Actor spell cards with no other pendulum monsters in the deck since it is Pure Abyss Actors. Making a build that relies on summoning Heavymetalfoes Electrumitegoing first and setting up interruptions could be a good meta deck once the new Abyss Actor cards come out in the TCG. I have found this deck to be most effective going second because you can actually OTK your opponent on that second turn! One cool combo I love in this deck is when you're going second and your opponent has a monster and you have none while you have Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser or Abyss Actor - Extras in your hand. You can summon one, or both of those monsters and then normal summon if you only special summoned one of the two to make Electrumite and send Abyss Actor - Wild Hope off Electrumite's effect. Then, you activate a scale and pop it using Electrumite's effect to add Wild Hope back to your hand and draw one. Next, activate Wild Hope in scale and any other Abyss Actor monster for the other scale and use Wild Hope's effect to make the other scale a nine scale. Lastly, pendulum summon four or five monsters and OTK! I love this combo because your opponent just gets OTKd out of nowhere and it's very funny. Hope you enjoy the deck and have fun figuring out all the other fun combos!

deck_excerpt: Thunder Dragonlord is a miserable card
deck_description:
It is hard to justify playing Thunder Dragonlord in a Thunder Dragon Deck. It is a Main Deck monster that requires you to banish a Level 8 or lower Thunder monster from hand or face-up field to Special Summon it from your hand. And the only benefits that it provides is banishing 2 cards from your GY including a Thunder monster during your opponent’s turn and targeting a Thunder monster you control to make it untargetable by your opponent’s effects for the turn and allowing you to send a Thunder Dragon card from Deck to GY during your End Phase. For starters, this card is a Main Deck card which means that you have to either draw it or search it. Second, it has a Summoning requirement similar to the Thunder Dragon Fusion Monsters. You can literally play Thunder Dragonduo which is a better card with a much easier and more generic Summoning condition. And third, while it can banish cards from your GY on your opponent’s turn to trigger your Thunder Dragon monsters, you can already accomplish that by banishing cards to protect Thunder Dragon Titan and with Titan being a much better card in general. There is little to no reason that can even compel you to play Thunder Dragonlord. But alas, it is a Level 9 monster which means that it is time for me to put it into a Prediction Princess Deck. And we still face the same problems with the card, primarily being that it has to be hard-drawn or searched and it has a pretty terrible Summoning requirement. I think that Thunder Dragon Prediction Princess as a Deck is completely fine. If you do manage to get Thunder Dragonlord on field and activate World Legacy Monstrosity, you are pretty much set. However, it is just so annoying to have to focus on searching for lord and making sure that the conditions are met to Special Summon it from hand. And you realistically do not end on anything unique as a part of your Endboard aside from your Prediction Princess stuff. It doesn’t have to, but seeing as how much effort you have to go through to actually get lord on field, I do wish that there was another pay-off. This Deck is like a 3.5 out of 10 on the Prediction Princess scale. Not to downplay Thunder Dragon, but just to make a point that Thunder Dragonlord is miserable.

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field either face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. We are playing 3 because we are running Pre-Preparation of Rites as a means of having at least something to end on or at least trying to get as far into our combo as possible if we are unable to access and make Thunder Dragonlord and have Monstrosity available. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned by Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down, and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY if she is Tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on the field, she gives your Rituals targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Because it is pretty hard to actually consistently Summon Thunder Dragonlord every game, we can at the very least make it to either Tarotrei or Tarotreith, especially with the help of Pre-Prep, so we are playing these 2 as targets in Deck for Monstrosity to Summon when targeting either Tarotrei or Tarotreith. Deus-X negates the activated effects of all of your opponent’s monsters on the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, it can add a Level 9 monster with a different original Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. Pot of the Forbidden allows you to draw 2 cards, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, return all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card back into the Deck, whichever effect of your choice if it is flipped face-up. 3 Aloof Lupine. On Normal Summon, you can banish a monster from hand and banish a monster from Deck with the same type as that monster. And if it is destroyed by battle or your opponent’s card effect you can add back 1 of your banished monsters. This card is really good for triggering your Thunder Dragon effects, whichever you need, as long as you have 1 in hand to banish first. This can basically help you to access Thunder Dragonlord, but it can fail to do so if you are unable to meet its Summoning requirement after searching it. Moving onto the Thunder Dragons, 2 Thunder Dragonlord, 3 Thunder Dragonroar, 2 Thunder Dragonhawk, and 3 Thunder Dragondark. We will not be making use of any of lord’s effects, and we are only using its effect to Summon itself from hand to get it on field as a target for Monstrosity. It requires you to banish a Level 8 or lower Thunder monster from hand or face-up field during the turn a Thunder monster’s effect was activated in the hand to Special Summon it from hand. It is such a steep condition, and to make matters worse, it requires you to banish a Level 8 or lower Thunder which means that we can’t run Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju in the Main because you cannot banish it for lord, even if it works as removal and a target in Deck for Monstrosity targeting Tarotreith (or Bibliomuse). The other Thunder Dragons allow you to only use 1 of their effects per turn and only once that turn. Roar discards itself to add back a Thunder Dragon card that is banished or in your GY, and it can Special Summon a Thunder Dragon monster from Deck in Defense, returning it to hand during the End Phase, if it is banished or sent from field to GY. Usually this is the way that you are going to be getting a Thunder onto field to banish to Summon lord. Hawk discards itself to Special Summon a Thunder Dragon that is banished or in your GY except itself, and if it is banished or sent from field to GY, you can shuffle any number of cards from your hand into the Deck and redraw the same number of cards. Hawk’s banish effect really isn’t too relevant in this Deck. Half of the time you just want to search for Pot of Prosperity and the drawing turns off your ability to activate Pot. Dark discards itself to add a Thunder Dragondark from Deck to hand and if it is banished or sent from field to GY, you can add a Thunder Dragon card from Deck to hand. This is how you are going to be searching for lord if you didn’t hard draw it, and if you did already draw lord, you can use it to get a Thunder Dragon whose effect you can activate in hand this turn to fulfill lord’s Summoning requirement.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for either Master of Ham or Kaminari Attack to go into Thunder Dragon Titan if you want to be cute. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual from hand or GY face-up or face-down, and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only be used to Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 2 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 1 Gold Sarcophagus which banishes a card from your Deck and you add that card to hand during the second Standby Phase after this card’s activation. This basically just triggers a Thunder Dragon from Deck. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which allows you to either Special a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9’s from Deck with a different Type and Attribute than the targeted monster with different names. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Thunder Dragon Titan which can be made by Tributing a Thunder monster from hand and a Thunder Fusion Monster you control which is going to be the 1 Kaminari Attack that we are playing. As a non-once per turn, it can pop a card on the field when a Thunder monster’s effect is activated in the hand, even during the Damage Step and it can protect itself from card effect destruction by banishing 2 cards from GY. You don’t really go into this guy, but in a situation where you already have all of your Prediction Princess and Ritual pieces and have Instant Fusion and another Thunder in hand, you can make it just to have a guy that stays on field who has the possibility of popping cards as well. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which can search a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck when it is sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which can send a card from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon and it can target monsters in GY up to the number of its materials, detach the same number of materials, and attach the targeted cards from GY. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, 1 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being. 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 2 Lightning Storm, 2 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: With our powers combined.. We make calamity!
deck_description:
I hope you liked fun, interactive and compelling back and forth, because this deck will definitely NOT do that! Sometimes anyway.

Centur-ion is a deck revolving around summoning level 12 synchro monsters! The downside is most of them need synchro tuners, multiple tuners, or specific named tuners. The upside is most of the best level 12 synchro's are completely generic!

The strong line this deck will do is normal summon Trudea, using its effect putting itself and Primera in the S/T zone, activate Primera to summon, us its effect to add Stand Up Centur-Ion!, activate it by sending anything from hand to grave, put Emeth VI in the S/T zone, activating Emeth VI and synchro summoning Legatia, drawing 1 card; finally, in the end phase, place Trudea in the S/T zone. This line will enable you to, in your opponents main phase, immediately activating Primera and Trudea in the S/T to summon them (making Trudea a level 8), then using Stand Up's 2nd effect to immediately synchro summon after getting a special summon to make Crimson Dragon. Then, use Crimson Dragon targeting Legatia to summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity and voila! your opponents turn is skipped giving you an easy otk turn 3!

The Horus card's allow for the easiest Zombie Vampire in the format, letting us mill 4 and praying we get lucky enough to grab any Centur-ion monster or another horus card! But they aren't just here to make Zombie Vampire either! Each Horus is also level 8, meaning them plus Primera makes any level 12 synchro! You also don't need to run as many Horus monsters either, just 3 Imsety and 1 Hapi are all that's required, I prefer the extra name as a just in case.

There are a ton of different ways to build this deck too! You can play pure, running desires, prosperity, bonfire, etc, you can play a bystial centric version, running Lubellion, Magnamhut, Druiswurm, Sarnoir and Branded Beast/Regained and also use them as level 8/6 cards to go into your 12s or 10s (part of the reason Chaos Angel and Baronne are in this list! Bystials in the side are the main enablers of them)

The funniest thing this deck can do is also hard summon ZEUS or TY-PHON because of how easily you can make 12 star synchros, meaning you can just make a calamity board going first and then, if you somehow can't get to an OTK, just summon ZEUS post battle! 

I should also note I'm extremely inexperienced with the deck, so please go and find other guides or watch other people play this deck to get a better handle on how to pilot this deck more adeptly Joshua Schmidt just uploaded a vid on his 2nd channel (link here) of him playing against Quantal on Lab while he played Centur-Ion, it's a great way to get an understanding on how to play this deck when you're on the backfoot constantly.

SUPER

Just a casual labrynth deck.

Works okay against kashtira

My approach to this deck is a hyper-consistent and flexible combo deck.

I play 40 cards, however i think the deck can go up to 45 without the consistency suffering greatly.

 

Why no Chaos Angel?

I don't like it very much, I think it's too expensive to summon for not really lucrative payout. Having to use a Seyfert or Wyverbuster and a Bystial to make protect your synchros in a deck that does just fine ending on Borrelend (which has its own protection) and I:P (to enable S:P Little Knights on-summon effect) doesn't seem exactly optimal (I might be biased from older builds played since I've been playing Dragon Link since the Rokket Revolt structure deck was released, I am open to discussion)

 

Why Ty-Phon?

The deck is, unsuprisingly, due to its amount of engine very competent at breaking boards. (Borrelends effect to attack each each monster can be devastating since its high ATK-stat and innate protection) However it does sometimes struggle to out monsters that cannot be targeted and/or destroyed if you don't have access to board breakers like DRNM, Droplet or Eclipse (and even if you did play one of those options, you'd still have to draw them) so having a pretty much instant out to those monsters helps the deck a lot. You could also play Armageddon Chaos Emperor as a board breaker, but depending on the gamestate and matchup that can be a very expensive card to resolve, especially if your opponent has follow-up.

 

I only play one Druiswurm since I don't like drawing multiple Bystials outside of the Tearlament-matchup where, due to the nature of the Tearlament monsters effects, Druiswurm is not an optiomal option (also explaining the three Baldrake in the side deck, I think it's the best Bystial specifically against Tearlament and Branded)

Maindecking no handtraps except Nibiru comes from me not wanting to play any handtraps that don't work with Chaos Space (I think Nibiru is a great option this format, but Veiler is decent as well)

The Phantazmay in the side deck is for the Unchained matchup or the mirror match (the draw and the target negate are great in both of those matchups and you can add Phantazmay off Magnamut going first, adding an extra layer of interaction to your board).

Chaos Emperor Armageddon is a great side-option against backrow-heavy matchups where it's rare to be able to summon Ty-Phon. (It's also a great option for turn three, especially to clean-up a board to find the kill. Just like Phantazmay, you could add this off a turn-one Magnamut)

Elsewise the build is very standard.

 

GLHF,

Playing Style

"Memento" is a theme focused on speedily filling the GY with many copies of its monsters in order to facilitate the Special Summon of its boss monster; "Mementoal Tecuhtlica - Combined Creation", which is able to attack all of the opponent's monsters once each when by itself on the field and Special Summons "Memento" monsters from the hand and GY when the opponent uses a card or effect. All "Memento" monsters, barring "Tecuhtlica", have effects that can destroy a "Memento" monster(s) you control in order to do various other effects; from searching cards to setting up the GY by sending monsters from the Deck to the GY for explosive plays with "Tecuhtlica". The two Level 1 monsters of the theme, "Mementotlan Goblin" and "Mementotlan Mace", also function as Hand trap cards while controlling "Tecuhtlica"; "Goblin" being able to prevent "Memento" monsters from being targeted with card effects for the turn while "Mace" is able to take control of an opponent's monster until the end of the turn.

One simple method to Special Summon "Mementoal Tecuhtlica - Combined Creation" requires only "Mementotlan Angwitch". When it is Summoned, it can add "Mementotlan Tatsunootoshigo" to the hand, which can Special Summon itself. Then, it can destroy itself to send "Mementotlan Mace", "Mementotlan Goblin", and a second copy of "Mementotlan Angwitch" from the Deck to the GY. Next, "Mementotlan Angwitch" can destroy itself to Summon "Mementotlan Goblin" from the GY, which can destroy itself to send "Mementotlan-Horned Dragon" and "Mementoral Tecuhtlica" from the Deck to the GY. Finally, "Mementoral Tecuhtlica" can Special Summon itself from the GY by shuffling "Fairywitch", "Tatsunootoshigo", "Mace", "Goblin", and "Horn Dragon" back into the Deck. If this combo is started by using "Mementotlan Dark Blade" to Summon "Mementotlan Angwitch" from the Deck, "Goblin" can send one of the archetype's Spell/Trap Cards instead.

deck_excerpt: Branded Chimera  / Asunción WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Oscar Espinola

Tournament: Asunción WCQ Regional – November 11th 2023

Placement: Top 8

What Does This Deck Do?

- This deck utilises the Infinitrack core Monsters to Special Summon as many EARTH Machine Monsters that you possibly can in a turn to either XYZ Summom other Infinitrack Monsters that can steal your opponant's Monsters after destroying them, or to LINK Summon other Machine Monsters to help you or hinder your opponant.

How Does This Deck Work?

- The ultimate plan is to get your Signature Monster, Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe out as quickly as possible. This is accomplished by wither Leveling up your Infinitrack XYZ Monsters with Outrigger Extension each turn, or by utilising the Level 10 Machine Monsters to XYZ Summon Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max , who can then XYZ Summon into Liebe.

[Note: I do recommend activating Gustav Max's Effect 1st before XYZ Summoning, as that is an instant 2000 Damage to your opponant for free]

What Makes Infinitrack Monster So Special?

- Infinitrack Effect Monsters have effects that can make themselves Special Summon to the Field, and sometimes bring other Earth Machine Monster Cards with them, making them useful for when you need extra Monsters on the Field.

The XYZ Monsters all have their own effects, as well as a shared effect that allows you to steal your opponant's destroyed cards and use them as XYZ Satellites. This means that you can start storing Satellites to use for Liebe to give it even more firepower and attack opprotunities.

The LINK Monsters we have are Infinitrack Goliath , which is a LINK Monster primarily used to become a XYZ Satellite for an extra defensive bonus for that monster, and then your Boss Monster, Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops , whose not only a strong LINK Monster, but this card's effect allows it to return return an XYZ Monster from your Graveyard to your Field, even if you use it to Summon I.F.M, and steal ANY card on your opponant's side of the field and turn it into a Satellite for said XYZ Monster.

So Why the Level 10 Monsters?

- All the Level 10s are primarily just to help you get to Liebe faster, but do not be afraid to use them for other purposes as well. Especially Snow Plow Hustle Rustle , as its effect is activated when you are attacked directly. I also placed a Train Connection Spell Card to boost any Monsters Attack more should you have 2x Level 10 Monsters in your Graveyard.

Any Other Useful Gimmicks I Should Know?

- Construction Train Signal Red : Useful for when you want to stop one of your Monsters being desroyed or you being attacked directly, as it can then be Special Summoned and tank the hit from the attacking Monster. IT IS RECOMMENDED TO ALWAYS SPECIAL SUMMON THIS IN DEFENCE MODE!

Crusher Run / Spin Turn : Use these Traps to destroy cards on your opponant's Field.

Clockwork Night - A helpful Field Spell to slowly boost your Monsters, but to also hinder and weaken your enemy's cards.

Barrage Blast - Use this Trap Card should you have a lot of excess XYZ Satellites to decimate your opponant's Field

 

This is just a Deck I tend to have more fun than being serious with, but you want to put in any recommendations or constructive critism feel free to moention it in the Comments.

Happy Duelling!

deck_excerpt: A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create a Kozmo deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"
deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create a Kozmo deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

Deck Strategy:

Spaceships and Pilots: Kozmo monsters come in two types: the large spaceships (Dark Destroyer, Forerunner, Sliprider, etc.) and the small pilots (Farmgirl, Soartroopers, Wickedwitch, etc.). The spaceships can float into each other when destroyed, maintaining field presence.

Kozmotown: Kozmotown is a crucial field spell. It allows you to recover banished Kozmo monsters, recycle your resources, and draw cards.

Emergency Teleport: This spell card is essential for bringing out your Kozmo pilots quickly. It enables Synchro plays and provides easy access to Kozmo Farmgirl for direct attacks and searching.

Kozmojo: Kozmojo is a powerful trap that not only banishes opposing monsters but also lets you tag out your own Kozmo monster for another one.

Kozmo Lightsword: This spell provides both offensive and defensive capabilities. It can be used to deal damage, clear your opponent's field, or recover banished Kozmo monsters.

Extra Deck: While Kozmo decks primarily focus on their main deck monsters, having an Extra Deck is essential. Cyber Dragon Infinity, Psy-Framelord Omega, and other generic Level 6 and Rank 4 monsters can be useful in various situations.

Side Deck: Customize your Side Deck based on the local meta. Hand traps, additional removal, or anti-meta cards can be useful.

deck_excerpt: Almost likely to troll your opponent.
deck_description: A little something tells me inside me deeply if this work best without any spellcards except the field one.

Playing style

"Snake-Eye" is a theme focused around Level 1 FIRE monsters and Special Summoning monsters from the Spell & Trap Zone treated as Continuous Spell Cards. The bulk of its monster line-up is made of Level 1 FIRE Pyro monsters that feature various consistency effects as well as a shared effect to send themselves and another card the player controls to Special Summon a "Snake-Eye" monster from the hand or Deck, excluding that respective card. The boss of the theme is "Snake-Eyes Flamberge Dragon", a Level 8 FIRE Dragon monster able to place any monster on the field or in either GY on the field as a Continuous Spell Card to its owner's field. On top of this, during the opponent's turn, it is able to take a monster treated as a Continuous Spell and Special Summon it to the field of its controller, leading to passive snatching of the opponent's stronger monsters.

 

The theme is supported by three Spell Cards and one Trap Card primarily. The original card for the theme, "Sinful Spoils of Subversion - Snake-Eye", is a basic Spell Card able to place a monster on either side of the field to the Spell & Trap Zone as a Continuous Spell. The Field Spell Card, "Divine Temple of the Snake-Eye", places a "Snake-Eye" monster onto the field as a Continuous Spell from hand, Deck, or GY, gives all Level 1 FIRE monsters a sizable stat gain of 1100 ATK, and is able to Special Summon a monster treated as a Continuous Spell to your field once per turn when the opponent Normal or Special Summons a monster. As well, the final Spell Card, "Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye", is able to summon any Level 1 FIRE monster from the hand or Deck and also can banish itself to add any Level 1 FIRE monster from the Deck to the hand at the added cost of placing a "Snake-Eye" or "Diabellstar" monster at the bottom of the deck, cementing a further connection between the two themes. The Trap Card of the theme, "Startling Stare of the Snake-Eyes", does much of the same things the rest of the theme can do such as placing monsters in the backrow and Special Summoning them back, but the user needs to have "Snake-Eye" monsters on the field whose Levels total to 2 or more.

Bystials also provide 6's and 8's to both expand and reinforce your Synchro plays. Baldrake can also perform some heavy lifting alongside Trudea on established boards, should the Calamity lock either be interupted or deemed sub-optimal.

deck_excerpt: You can't make me Summon Ancient Gear Megaton Golem
deck_description:
So Ancient Gears have 2 Level 9 monsters in their archetype: Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon and Ancient Gear Megaton Golem. You can tie me to a chair, electrocute me, do whatever to me, but you cannot make me even try to Summon Ancient Gear Megaton Golem. It's just an extremely worse Chaos Ancient Gear Giant that uses 3 Ancient Gears for material instead of 4 and it floats into Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem when destroyed by your opponent's effect. Like Chaos Giant is a win condition and Megaton Golem is just bad. And besides, Reactor Dragon is a much easier-to-access Level 9 monster in the Deck. To supplement Reactor Dragon, we are playing Geartown and Ancient Gear Catapult. Geartown can Special Summon an Ancient Gear monster from hand, Deck, or GY when it is destroyed and sent to the GY. Catapult has 2 effects. If you control no monsters, you can activate it from hand, targeting and destroying 1 face-up card you control, and if you do, you Special Summon 1 Ancient Gear monster from Deck ignoring its Summoning Conditions. And if it is in GY, you can banish it to target 1 face-up card you control, and destroy it, Special Summoning 1 Ancient Gear Token to your field. Now, you can only use 1 effect per turn and only once that turn, but for the most part, that's completely fine. Now the real magic happens when you draw both Geartown and Catapult. You can activate Geartown and destroy it with Catapult. The Chain resolves and Catapult Special Summons an Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon from Deck, and on a new Chain, Geartown Special Summons another Reactor Dragon from anywhere, giving you 2 Level 9 monsters to go into Aggregator to send Herald and so forth. You don't need to draw both Geartown and Catapult in the same hand, but we are playing a lot of cards to access both. And hey, we aren't playing World Legacy Monstrosity in this Deck which is a plus as it is an unsearchable card that we don't need to worry about drawing in this Deck.

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. You know the drill: Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during the End Phase. Tarotreith can be either Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down, and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Summon herself back from GY if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she is face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. We are only playing 1 Deus-X Krawler. You don't need to play 2 as we don't have Monstrosity in this Deck as we aren't relying on it and since the Attributes of our monsters don't work with Monstrosity. After it has been flipped face-up, it negates the activated monster effects of monsters on your opponent's side of the field and if it is destroyed on field, you can add a Level 9 monster from Deck to hand with a different Type and Attribute than it. If you want, you can also play 1 Pot of the Forbidden as another Flip option or if you draw Deus-X in your starting hand. Just cut a Pre-Preparation of Rites or a Clockwork Night. 2 Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon. It's effects literally do not matter as you are only using it as a Level 9 Ancient Gear that you can Special Summon via Geartown and Ancient Gear Catapult. And it's okay if you draw 1 of them as Geartown can Summon it from hand, Deck, or GY, but you need at least 1 in Deck as Catapult only Special Summons from Deck. 3 Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede. On Normal or Special Summon, it can target and Special Summon an EARTH Machine monster from your GY in Defense with its effects negated. And it can also target 1 other face-up monster you control, and change its Level to the Level of the targeted monster or make the targeted monster's Level become its Level. But you cannot attack this turn except with Xyz Monsters. Pegasus can Special Summon back an Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon that is in your GY and target it to make itself a Level 9, giving you 2 Level 9 monsters to go into Aggregator. You may remember this card from Rank 10 Trains, and here, it functionally accomplishes the same thing to go into a Rank 9 Xyz Monster. Flying Pegasus can be used Turn 1 if you send Reactor Dragon from Deck to GY via Foolish Burial, which we are playing, or we can discard it for the GY effect of Clockwork Night. However, it has a lot of application on following turns. For example, you can Normal Summon it, bring back a Reactor Dragon, make Pegasus a Level 9, and go into either Infinitrack Earth Slicer or Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows. Earth Slicer can then detach 2 Xyz Materials to pop 2 cards on the field, attach with Earth Slicer, attach the monster it destroys by battle to it, and overaly into a live Zeus. Laevateinn, can tribute itself to Special Summon Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity from Extra Deck and attach 2 cards on field or in either GY to it as Xyz Material. Now, you can't attack this turn except with Machine Xyz Monsters, but you can just make Earth Slicer to clear some of the board and attack as it is a Machine Xyz Monster. And for our final monster, 3 Planet Pathfinder. You can Tribute it to search a Field Spell, which is always Geartown in this Deck. You have no Normal Summon in this Deck. You could argue that Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede is a Normal Summon, but it doesn't have application unless you have Reactor Dragon in GY. And we don't need to necessarily play Diviner of the Herald or Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands because we are playing Pre-Preparation of Rites and it is relatively easy to make Mereologic Aggregator in this Deck without relying on World Legacy Monstrosity. Therefore, we are playing Planet Pathfinder to have more ways to search for Geartown. And since it Tributes itself from field to search a Field Spell, this leaves you with no monsters on field, allowing you to activate Ancient Gear Catapult from hand. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion which gets you to Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Ancient Gear Catapult. As said before, if you control no monsters, you can target a face-up card you control and destroy it to Special Summon an Ancient Gear monster from Deck ignoring its Summoning Conditions. And in GY, you can banish it to destroy a face-up card you control to Special Summon an Ancient Gear Token which is a Level 1 EARTH Machine ATK 0/DEF 0 token. This goes along with our 3 copies of Geartown which can Special Summon an Ancient Gear monster from your hand, Deck, or GY if it is destroyed and sent to GY. 1 Terraforming as another way to search for Geartown. 1 Foolish Burial which has a couple of applications. It can send a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from Deck to GY as Underworld Ritual of Prediction can Ritual Summon from GY. And you can send an Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon as Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede can Special Summon it back from GY, copying its Level, and going into a Rank 9. Also, Geartown can Summon from GY, so it's all good. 2 Foolish Burial Goods which can send a Spell/Trap from Deck to GY. Our targets are Ancient Gear Catapult and Clockwork Night. We are playing 2 Clockwork Night which we are only using for its GY effect which allows you to banish it can discard a card to add an EARTH Machine monster from your Deck to hand. This searches you either Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede to possibly make a Rank 9 or Planet Pathfinder in order to search for Geartown. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only be used to Ritual Summon Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. And finally, 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 3 Mereologic Aggregator. On Xyz Summon, it can send a monster from Extra Deck to GY. And you can target monsters in your GY up to the number of its materials, detach the same number of materials, and attach those monsters from GY to it. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Nine-Lives Cat which gives your monsters that were Special Summoned from the GY with targeting protection from your opponent's effects and you can detach 1 Xyz Material to either target a Level 9 monster in your GY or a monster in your opponent's GY and Special Summon it. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Contact "C". 3 Forbidden Droplet. 2 Lightning Storm. 1 Harpie's Feather Duster. 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

deck_description:
I love this deck because apart from Magnifica, the deck is so affordable! 

Exosister is an anti-GY strategy which utilizes Rank 4 XYZ monsters to control the game and punish the use of the Graveyard! If an opponent tries to move cards out of their grave, you get to XYZ summon on their turn! Since you don't use your own GY you're free to play brutial cards like Dimension Shifter to skip your opponent's turn and then destroy them with powerful cards like Exosister Magnifica. 

This deck would be much cheaper without Magnifica, but it is a price we have to pay for power. If you want to upgrade this further, you just need an extra copy of Exosister Magnifica to improve things a lot.

deck_excerpt: Control the game with an arsenal of powerful Spells!
deck_description: Sky Striker is in a lot of ways YGO's answer to mono blue. If you like countering your opponent's gameplan and drawing cards, this is the deck for you!
Locals: Tistina Mayakashi (OTS CHAMPIONSHIP 18.11.2023)

I know these archetypes have absolutely no compatiblity but as far as I know, their lore is linked with each other. Much like all the other decks I make where I mix archetypes, this deck does not work in practical use I am sure. But still, the cards are fun to use so go wild!

This deck can very easily FTK any deck in the game. With the agents of creation and destruction - venus you will be able to summon up to nine (if you have the sanctum of parshath + the chorus in the sky on the field/hand it becomes eleven) mystical shine balls per turn. The deck is centered around getting agent of creation - venus to your graveyard or hand and summoning it (normally, or with neptune) to summon your mystical balls. You will then be able to send majesty hyperion to the graveyard with moon and then you can special summon it from the graveyard (by banishing neptune to also get the sanctuary in the sky) all while link summoning celestial knightlord (before or after) with the rest of your mystical balls & venus. You can then search out archlord kristya and then special summon it with celestial knightlords effect (or its own) when you link summon s:p knight with moon and majesty hyperion. The great part about this is during your turn you will be able to banish archlord kristya with s:p knight if your opponent activates a card, allowing you to continue the turn as normal, and archlord kristya will still be on the field during your oponents turns (if you happen to not FTK because he negates archlords effect somehow). If you decide not to go this route, you can always use venus and the mystical balls in conjunction with uranus and the master/majesty hyperions to summon masterflare hyperion, who then will use its effect to mimic the agent of destruction - venus effect, and summon three more mystical balls. Once you use those three, you can summon another three with the agent of creation - venus you already have on the field, this will lead into a mekk-knight, bow of the goddess, masterflare hyperion combo. There is a good chance you will still have divine punishment in your hand as well after all that. If the game ends up going late, you can always rely on the topologic + angel of zera combo which sets a continuous loop of summoning and banishing that would increase topologics attack power repeatedly and clear the board every other turn (lmao so ridiculous). This deck is just a nightmare to deal with. That being said, the deck has a small chance of not getting the cards you need in your hand (too many mystical balls) and you are left with almost nothing in your first turn. This deck provides outstanding negation, summoning, search ability, and attack power. One of the most absurd decks you will ever play.  - Created by dg
