Predaplant Ambulomelides is literally a custom card. Being able to search a Predaplant monster or Predap Spell/Trap on Fusion Summon and being able to Tribute a Predaplant to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck is so incredibly powerful. And in the case of this Deck, it, alongside Ultra Polymerization and Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, gets you to Predaplant Triphyoverutum through a single card and a monster discard. From there, if you have World Legacy Monstrosity in hand, you can target Triphy to get Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler (or Trias Hierarchia) from Deck, overlaying Triphy and Deus into the Aggregator line. Or, if you have enough Ritual fodder in hand or once you have enough after activating Pot of Prosperity, you can go into Tarotrei and play with whatever Flips you have on hand while having an Extra Deck Special Summon negate through Triphy. I really like how this Deck came out, and it even shares the core components of Master of Ham Prediction Princess, which is a Deck that I have continuously said that I really like, especially for a Prediction Princess variant. Instead of searching Ultra Poly with Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra, you can search for Instant Fusion, Link into Cross-Sheep, Instant Fusion into Master of Ham to one of Cross-Sheep's Zones, Summon Bibliomuse from Deck, Summon a Level 4 or lower back from GY with Cross-Sheep, and have material for Apollousa with Bibliomuse access on hand, just like you would in Ham Prediction Princess. This Deck takes everything from Ham Prediction Princess and adds on to it, making it, in my opinion, a more interesting and more fun Deck to play. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster face-up or face-down and can Special Summon a Flip Monster face-down during the End Phase from hand or GY. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. It can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down and on flip, it can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse this card can Summon itself back face-down if it is Tributed and sent to the GY, and if it is flipped face-up, it can search for a Prediction Princess, other than itself, and a Ritual Spell from Deck. And while it is face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of all monsters on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and it can add a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than itself if it is destroyed on field. 1 Trias Hierarchia which can be sent off of Diviner or Special Summoned off of the effect of World Legacy Monstrosity targeting Predaplant Triphyoverutum on the field and Hierarchia can also Tribute a Fairy to Summon itself from hand or GY. 1 Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light which is a Level 9 LIGHT Plant monster which means that Monstrosity can Special Summon it from Deck when targeting Triphyoverutum on field. On Normal or Special Summon, you can add a Generaider card or a Plant monster from your Deck to your hand. Since we are playing Lonefire, you can get this card out of the Deck with it, and if you have Monstrosity in hand, you can target it to get Bibliomuse and Deus-X out of the Deck to have both Bibliomuse access and Rank 9 access. You could play Impcantation Talismandra instead of Mardel because it is also a Plant that Lonefire can get and it searches for a Ritual Monster when Special Summoned from Deck. But I still like Mardel better as it is a Level 9 target for Monstrosity both on field and in Deck. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra, and 2 Predaplant Chlamydosundew. Scorpio can discard a monster on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant Monster from Deck. You are always Special Summoning Cobra with this effect as Cobra searches for a Fusion or Polymerization Spell from Deck when it is Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster once per Duel. Your options in this Deck are Ultra Polymerization and Instant Fusion. If you want to go through the Master of Ham line because you have the Ritual pieces already assembled in hand, you search for Instant Fusion. If you have Monstrosity, you search Ultra Poly to Fuse into Predaplant Ambulomelides and go forth from there. Chlamydosundew on field can Fusion Summon a DARK Fusion Monster from Extra Deck by using monsters from your hand, field, and/or monsters your opponent controls with Predator Counters as Fusion Material including itself. After you Ultra Poly Scorpio and Cobra into Melides, Melides searches for a copy of Predapruning which I will talk about later on, but you would then use the effect of Ultra Poly in GY, banishing it to Special Summon both Scorpio and Cobra from GY as they were used as Material for the Fusion Summon by Ultra Poly. Melides would then Tribute any Predaplant monster to Special Summon Chlamy from Deck. Now that you have 3 DARK monsters on field, you can now Fuse using Chlamy’s effect to Fusion Summon Predaplant Triphyoverutum. 3 Diviner of the Herald which can send a Fairy monster from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon. 2 Lonefire Blossom which can Tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. And 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham or Predaplant Ambulomelides which is definitely a Summonable target. I haven’t experimented much with Instant Fusioning into Melides in this Deck, but presumably, if you already have Bibliomuse access, you could go into Melides and see if you have any plays from there. 1 Ultra Polymerization which Fusion Summons using exactly 2 monsters you control by paying 2000 Life Points. Neither player can activate cards or effects in response to the activation. You can banish this card from GY to target a Fusion Monster that was Fusion Summoned via this card’s effect and Special Summon all the Fusion Materials used to make it from your GY with their effect negated and ATK/DEF reduced to 0. 1 Predapruning which is an Equip Spell that targets and Special Summons a Predaplant monster from your GY and equips it with this card. This can Special Summon any Predaplant monster, including Predaplant Triphyoverutum. So, after Triphy ends up in the GY, you can Special Summon it back with Predapruning to use as material for a Rank 9 play, to go into Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows or to use as more Link Material. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon 1 Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters with a different Type and Attribute than the targeted monster with different names. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Predaplant Triphyoverutum which requires 3 DARK monsters on field as Fusion material and if your opponent would Special Summon a monster(s) from the Extra Deck while you control this Fusion Summoned card, you can negate the Summon and destroy those monsters. We are mainly getting Triphy out for a Level 9 on field for Monstrosity, but you could use it as interruption if you already have all of your Ritual pieces in hand. And it is important to note that Triphy cannot negate Extra Deck Special Summons after it has been brought back by Predapruning. Best that it can do at that point is be used for a Rank 9 or as Link Material. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which needs 2 Predaplant monsters as Fusion Material and on Fusion Summon, it can add a Predaplant Monster or a Predap Spell/Trap from Deck to hand which is always going to be Predapruning unless you’ve already drawn it, otherwise you can add anything. It can also target 1 monster you control or 1 monster your opponent controls with a Predator Counter and Tribute it to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck. You are always getting Chlamy with this effect for the ability to Fusion Summon again. 1 Starving Venom Fusion Dragon, 1 Garura, Wings of Resonant Life, and 1 Mudragon of the Swamp which are Super Poly targets. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell when sent to GY. You can definitely play 2 in case you draw Diviner and Trias Hierarchia, so you could cut 1 of your Super Poly Targets for the second Herald. 1 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. 1 Cross-Sheep. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller.

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: “醉影剑魂”

Tournament: Asia Campus League 2023 Hong Kong – October 28th 2023

Placement: Top 4

This deck has taken a bit of time and testing to get right but as of now it works very consistently and leaves you with a very powerfull end board. For full combo (without getting interrupted) all you need in the starting hand is access to a live twin monster (other then frost or treat) and access to an unchained trap. With this you should be able to end on Evil★Twin Trouble Sunny, Unchained Soul of Rage, D/D/D Wave High King Caesar and whatever trap you started with. You can potentially have Linguriboh up if you have a live☆twin in hand as well as frost or treat in hand to overcome evenly matched. If you're opponent is running monster destruction cards like lightning storm and raigeki then you can summon muckracker to the field during the combo to protect your cards however, you won't be able to set a trap is you choose this option.

Combo 1 (Regular Combo):

Step 1: First you are gonna want to do your twin combo up Trouble Sunny (I would recommend not drawing with Ki-sikil unless you have to incase your opponent is playing droll and lock bird).

Step 2: Use Trouble Sunny effect to bring back both Evil★Twins Lil-la and Ki-sikil and link them into Unchained Soul Lord of Yama. Use Yama's summon effect to search Unchained Twins - Aruha.

Step 3: Set your unchained trap and use Aruha effect to destroy it and special summon itself to the field. On resolution use the unchained trap effect to special summon Unchained Twins - Sarama to the field.

Step 4: Use Sarama effect to set the unchained trap from the grave and destroy Aruha. Next, use Aruha effect to special summon Unchained Soul of Shyama to the field.

Step 5: Link Shyama and Yama into Unchained Soul of Rage. Then use Shyama effect from the grave to destroy Sarama and special summon itself to the field. On resolution, use Sarama effect to special summon Unchained Soul of Sharvara from the deck and use Yama effect at the same time to special summon Trouble Sunny from the grave.

Step 6: Overlay Shyama and Sharvara into D/D/D Wave High King Caesar and that is your setup.

 

Combo 2 (Linguriboh):

Its the same combo as before but after summoning your live twin to special summon its counter part from the deck, your special summon either frost or treat from hand, link into Linguriboh and carry on the combo as normal.

 

Combo 3 (Muckracker):

Carry on the normal combo up to adding Aruha to hand. Use aruha effect as normal to special summon itself to the field and special summon Sarama from the trap effect. Then you want to link Aruha and Yama into Muckracker. Once you have done that you then want to use Sarama effect to set Aruha and then destroy Aruha. This will trigger Aruha's effect to special summon Shyama from deck and Yama effect to special summon Trouble Sunny from grave. You then want to use Shyama effect on field to destroy Sarama which will activate Sarama's effect to special summon Sharvara from the deck. You then want to link these two into Unchained Soul of Rage and use Sharvara's effect to set the other trap card that you haven't used this turn (this part is very important). After that you want to use Shyama's effect from grave to special summon itself to the field by destroying that new set trap card. On resolution you want to use the trap card effect to special summon another Sharvara and then overlay into your D/D/D monster.

 

If you do choose to use this deck or a version of it please let me know how it performs as it has been doing very well for me atm.

deck_name: Centur-Ion Control (MORE THAN JUST CALAMITY TURBO!)
deck_excerpt: Centur-Ion is much more than "Calamity" turbo when it's played with a ton of purple cards!
deck_description:
A new mecha archetype has hit the Yugioh world by storm, and they are none other than Centur-Ions (the TCG name STILL weirds me out lol)! 

 

These machine pilots turbo excel in turboing out level 12 Synchros like no tomorrow, leading to the summon of their primary mechanical win condition - Legatia, draw 1, destroy 1, and end-phase resource generator. However, an ugly face has shown itself once again with the second coming of a "Calamity Lock" in the form of Crimson Dragon -> Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity. 

 

King Calamity is the true current win condition that Centur-Ion plays right now for competitive success unfortunately, which makes the deck a boring one-trick-pony. Despite the extreme consistency of the deck with 13+ one card starters and incredible grindgame, the deck has difficulty winning with its singular interruption or immediately OTKing the turn after without something supremely oppressively powerful, and King Calamity fits the bill. The King Calamity line is somewhat like a "glass cannon," prone to losing to a single well-timed handtrap or interruption, so despite the decks initial competitive hype, it may be weaker than it is sought out to be. 

 

So despite these flaws, what can be done to *fix* Centur-Ion? Turning to a "control" playstyle with traps - and LOTS OF THEM! With the opponent's gameplan slowed to a halt while you gather resources and summon beatsticks, Centur-Ion can win, even without it's calamitous crutch! (Shoutout to Yacine656 for this decklist and strategy, check his video out!)

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The CENTURION deck core is compact because of it's amazing consistency and 1-card starters being only a mere 15 cards. The only Centur-Ion cards that aren't a 1 card starter is Emet VI and Phalanx. Terraforming searches Stand-Up Centur-Ion which by extension is another starter. This brings the deck's total to 13 one-card starters, meaning that having them in your opening hand is extremely likely.
 
6 FLOODGATES are maindecked in this strategy, being x3 Skill Drain and x3 There Can Be Only One. While your strategy plays unimpeded, your opponent likely cannot play, vastly giving the Centur-Ion player the advantage.
 
6 SOLEMN cards are played. While notorious for In conjunction for being played defensively, solemn cards can also be used offensively! With the other traps in this deck, Judgment and Strike break boards very easily (for ex. you flip Skill Drain, opponent tries to negate with Baronne, and you counter with Solemn Strike!), allowing the Centur-Ion strategy to play out with safety. 
 
7 NORMAL TRAPS are used in this deck for their power and utility. Again, in conjunction with other traps, Imperms, IDP and Daruma Cannon can pick apart boards to simplify the gamestate so that the Centur-Ion strategy can shine. 
 
6 CARDS THAT USE EXTRA DECK are included, that being x3 Super Polymerization and x3 Pot of Prosperity. The Extra Deck is very loose and customizable with Centur-Ion, so board breaking ability with Super Poly and consistency boosts with Prosperity are used to take advantage of the Extra Deck space. 
 
You may have noticed no handtraps are maindecked with this build of Centur-Ion. This is because handtraps are best in decks that have a solid and robust gameplan so that handtrap interruption can support the strategy. Currently, Centu-Ion seems too frail to withstand too much interruption, so slowing down and simplifying the game with traps seems to be the ideal gameplan (also budget, since the alternative is the Horus engine). 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Centur-Ion's current main combo is linear, and all cards do the same thing and lead to the same outcome. This means that this deck is extremely predictable, very simple and easy to learn. As said before, most Centur-Ion cards are one card starters, and if your first starter gets interrupted/negated, the other starters in your hand can also act as extenders to continue on your combo. For example, if Primera got impermed/veiler'd, you can summon Primera and continue comboing to get your level 12 synchro boss monster, Legatia. 
 
Here is Centur-Ion 1-card combo:
 
Primera = Legatia (Pop monster, draw 1 and resource generator) + Calamity Lock (Or Omni-negate with Blazar Dragon) + follow-up 
  1. Normal summon Primera to search Stand-Up! 
  2. Activate Stand-Up! Use Stand-Up's effect to send 1 card from hand to GY to place Trudea on the backrow as a continuous trap. 
  3. Special summon Trudea from the backrow. 
  4. Activate Trudea's effect to place itself on the backrow and Emeth VI from deck on the backrow. 
  5. Special summon Emeth VI from the backrow. 
  6. Synchro summon Legatia using Primera + Emeth VI.
  7. Activate Legatia's on-summon effect to pop a monster with highest ATK your opponent controls (if applicable) and draw 1 card. 
  8. During the End Phase, activate Legatia's effect to place Primera on the backrow as a continuous trap.
  9. During the opponent's Main Phase, special summon Primera (CL1) and Trudea as a level 8 (CL2) from the backrow. 
  10. CL1 Primera to search a Centur-Ion card (usually Bonds since it's excellent follow-up), and CL2 Stand-Up to synchro summon using Primera + Trudea for Crimson Dragon. 
  11. Activate Crimson Dragon targeting Legatia to synchro summon King Calamity from Extra Deck. (If your opponent interrupts Crimson Dragon so that King Calamity loses it's timing window to resolve it's on-summon effect, summon Blazar Dragon instead). 
With one singular card, you've locked your opponent out of the game, and you have ample follow-up for next turn's OTK! (So unfair, I can feel a King Calamities ban on the horizon). 
 
In addition to the King Calamity Lock, the win condition of Centur-Ion is to outgrind your opponent with immense resource generation with Legatia's +1 draw and end phase recursion of Centur-Ion monster cards. If you've slowed down your opponent enough with your trap cards, floodgates and Mr. Calamity, you should be able to out-resource your opponent and win!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • If your opponent interrupts Crimson Dragon so that King Calamity loses it's timing window to resolve it's on-summon effect, summon Blazar Dragon instead. King Calamity is a "when" effect, so it's summon has to be the last thing in a chain - meaning Crimson Dragon's effect to summon Calamity should be the ONLY thing happening for Calamity's "when" effect to resolve successfully. 
  • Be aware of There Can Only Be One's effect to lock your own combo out from resolving. For example, if you already have Legatia on-board, you cannot summon Emeth VI!
  • If your opponent is targeting your Centur-Ion monster, you can "dodge" their targeting effect if Emeth VI is in your hand or GY! Simply chain Emeth VI's effect to place your monster in the backrow! 
  • If your opponent targets your continuous trap card Centur-Ion monster on the backrow during the main phase, you can "dodge" their targeting effect by simply chaining their quick effect summon! 
  • Centur-Ion Phalanx can banish your continuous trap card monsters in the backrow to summon them next stand-by phase. That's because monsters treated as continuous traps in the backrow are still counted as "monsters" and Phalanx reads "target 1 face-up monster card on the field."
  • Trap cards are surprisingly effective breaking boards going second. For example, A Skill Drain/Ice Dragon's Prison/Daruma Cannon paired with a Solemn Strike can break open boards with multiple negates! The turn after, you can play your Centur-Ion cards unimpeded. 
  • If Skill Drain is active on the field, Stand-Up! in the field zone while Primera is in the backrow as a trap and a potential level 8 (Trudea or Emeth VI), you can still search with Primera! Summon both Primera and the level 8, then CL1 Primera's effect to search, CL2 Stand-Up! and summon Legatia. Primera left the field, allowing it resolve it's search effect despite Skill Drain!
  • When you're forced to play second, you can side out your solemns and floodgates for a grand total of 14 blind boardbreakers! You also have 3 Pot of Prosperity, so that means you'll always have access to ways to crack open your opponent's board. Once the gamestate is in your favour, you can continue your usual Centur-Ion strategy in main phase 2. 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Playing this deck, I discovered that Centur-Ion is much more than the infamous "King Calamity Turbo!" In fact, I hardly resolved that combo and effect - most games were actually decided on the relentless Centur-Ion grindgame and devastating impact of backrow traps! 
 
Playing first, this deck is basically guaranteed to win 90% of the time since you have Calamities Lock backed by cards like Solemn Strike and Judgement. Going second, boards are broken and gamestate simplified by trap card, allowing the Centur-Ion to shine - eventually out-resourcing the opponent!
 
The first wave of support for Centur-Ion is features a surprisingly consistent and robust strategy. Its no glass cannon either, it can take a couple interruptions and given the correct extender, keep on comboing to reach the deck's archetypal boss monster Legatia! I'm excited for the further support in store for these mecha ladies - surely it'll be good enough to pierce the heavens!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Believe me, I really tried to make Darklord Prediction Princess work
deck_description:
I'm not one of those people who actually say and believe that Branded Darklord is actually a viable Deck, and I am surely not a person who believes that Darklord is a good Deck in general. There are a few reasons why I dislike Darklord. The first is that the Deck is so incredibly bricky. You either draw the right cards or your don't, and it's not like you can fix your hand with Indulged Darklord all of the time because she locks you into Fairy monster effects for the rest of the turn which prevents you from using her in Decks that utilize Darklord as a supplemental engine. You have to draw the right cards or hope that your 2 draws with Darklord Ixchel manage to give you some assemblance of plays. Then, you have the Darklord clause of most of their monsters having some kind of Summoning restriction where they can only be Special Summoned once per turn like in the case of Darklord Ixchel, unable to be Special Summoned from Deck or GY like Darklord Asmodeus, or unable to be Special Summoned at all and must be Tribute Summoned like with Darklord Morningstar. This isn't too much of a problem, but it makes it very hard to "combo off" with the Deck in certain applications. And finally, Darklord Superbia misses timing when you Special Summon it via a Darklord monster's effect when you copy the effect of Darklord Contact in GY. By copying the effect, you Special Summon Superbia from GY, then, you shuffle the copy of Contact from GY into Deck with your last action being the shuffle and Superbia missing timing as it is a "When ____: You can" effect. Either way, this here is Tezcatlipoca Prediction Princess and I call it that because Darklord Tezcatlipoca is the only Darklord monster we are playing. I tried to play the Deck with Ixchel, Superbia, Nasten, and Tezcatlipoca, but it was insanely bricky and grabbing whatever card you wanted off of Pot of Prosperity was a lot better than having to discard Ixchel and another Darklord to hopefully find a card you needed in the 2 cards that you would draw with Ixchel's effect. And I ended up with this Deck which is somewhat similar of a concept to Sigrun Prediction Princess where you are wholly reliant on Diviner of the Herald to get you to 2 Level 9's to go into Mereologic Aggregator. However, your full combo to a Rank 9 in this Deck is Diviner + a Reborn Spell. Normal Summon Diviner, send Trias Hierarchia from Deck to GY, Tribute Diviner to Summon Hierarchia, Diviner Special Summons Trickstar Nightshade from hand or Deck, Link off Nightshade into Trickstar Bloom, Nightshade Special Summons itself back from GY since it was used as Link Material for a Trickstar monster, Link off Bloom and Nightshade into Condemned Darklord, discard 1 card to send Darklord Tezcatlipoca from Deck to GY, and use your Reborn Spell (Monster Reborn, Darklord Contact, or Banishment of the Darklords to search Contact) to bring back Tezcatlipoca from GY, giving you 2 Level 9's in Tezca and Hierarchia. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster face-up or face-down and can Special Summon a Flip Monster face-down during the End Phase from hand or GY. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. It can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down and on flip, it can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse this card can Summon itself back face-down if it is Tributed and sent to the GY, and if it is flipped face-up, it can search for a Prediction Princess, other than itself, and a Ritual Spell from Deck. And while it is face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of all monsters on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and it can add a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than itself if it is destroyed on field. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which allows you to draw 2 cards, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, return all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card back into the Deck, whichever effect of your choice if it is flipped face-up. 1 Trias Hierarchia which can Special Summon itself from hand or GY by Tributing a Fairy monster. 1 Darklord Tezcatlipoca which can only be Special Summoned once per turn and can pay 1000 during either player's turn to target a Darklord Spell/Trap in your GY and apply its effect, shuffling it back into the Deck after it resolves. You can use this effect to copy the effect of Banishment of the Darklords in order to add a copy of Darklord Contact from Deck to hand to have the ability to Special Summon Tezcatlipoca from GY again next turn for Rank 9 or Link plays. 3 Diviner of the Herald which can send a Fairy monster from Deck or Extra Deck to GY and if it is Tributed, you can Special Summon 1 Level 2 or lower Fairy monster from hand or Deck except itself. 1 Trickstar Nightshade. It is a Level 1 Fairy which means it can be Special Summoned by the effect of Diviner and if it is sent to the GY for the Link Summon of a Trickstar Link Monster, you can Special Summon it back to field, banishing it when it leaves the field. This makes Nightshade practically a 1-card Link-2 which is exactly what we are using it for in order to get to Condemned Darklord. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual from hand or GY face-up or face-down, and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only be used to Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 3 Darklord Contact which can Special Summon a Darklord monster from your GY in face-up Defense Position and you can only activate it once per turn. 3 Banishment of the Darklords which adds a Darklord card from your Deck to your hand and can only be activated once per turn. This basically gives you 3 extra copies of Contact. 1 Monster Reborn in case we don't have Contact or access to it. 3 Pot of Prosperity and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia, 1 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy. 1 Condemned Darklord which allows you to Tribute Summon a Fairy by banishing 2 monsters from GY instead of Tributing monsters from field. And you can also discard a card to take a Darklord monster and either add it to hand or send it to GY. 1 Trickstar Bloom which needs a Level 2 or lower Trickstar monster and is only being used to Link climb into Condemned Darklord with Trickstar Nightshade. And 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being. 3 Droll & Lock Bird, 1 Called By the Grave, 3 Forbidden Droplet, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

It's amazing how Batteryman has some of the most busted cards in Edison architype-wise, but no one cares because the card pool for them is so bad. Battery Charger is literally just a Monster Reborn for the low price of 500 LP, Industral Strength can pop monsters + backrow with a single banish, Short Circuit is a full opponent-only board wipe, Battery Pack is Call of the Haunted x2 etc etc. If any other deck had these (think Blackwing/Frog) they'd be broken. In here? Barely enough to make it playable lol

So yeah, this architype is not great in Edison. They haven't yet got that future support that'll make them a underrated FTK powerhouse with the right draws, so instead this functions more as a deck that uses them rather than a Batteryman deck, if that makes any sense. The deck can still pull out wins with the DandyQuickdraw engine splashing in well with the similarly well leveled Battery cards and helps to make better use of the milling that this deck needs in order to make Industral active.

Eternal Duelist Soul is a pretty cool GBA Game, it has nice events and considerable replayability. The Decks from this game are pretty iconic and, since WC2004's decks are stored in this website already, I might aswell do the same for this game. Both games have the some really random but fitting decks for each character (almost like their anime decks).

I found these Decklists online and I'm saving them here for anyone looking for them easily (while also doing it for me). I've also tried to sort the cards by strenght, while also keeping a good organization, so it's easier to check what cards in their decks we should pay more attention to.

True Kings are definitely Level 9 monsters, but I've held back on putting them in the same Deck as Prediction Princess for some time because you really have no cards that benefit from being sent to the GY. People have historically played monsters like True King Agnimazud, the Vanisher and True King Lithosagym, the Disaster in Dinosaur because you could pop Babycerasaurus, Petiteranodon, and Miscellaneousaurus with the True King effects to get the Baby effects upon their destruction and Misc hits the GY where it can now banish itself for its effect. And it is also generally good to have Dinosaurs in GY to get something like a Souleating Oviraptor from Deck via Misc's effect from banishing 4 Dinosaurs from GY. Prediction Princess and general Ritual and Flip Support Monsters do not have much benefit, if any at all, from being in the GY or being sent to the GY. Yes, you could technically Ritual Summon your Prediction Princess Ritual Monsters from GY with Underworld Ritual of Prediction, but you still need to play monsters of a specific Attribute to use the effects of the True King monsters. The True King-related Attributes that we have access to the most are WIND and EARTH for Mariamne, the True Dracophoenix and True King Lithosagym, the Disaster respectively. For WIND, we have things like World Legacy Guardragon Mardark, Spirit of the Fall Wind, and handtraps like Droll & Lock Bird and Ghost Mourner & Moonlit Chill. For EARTH, we have things like Prediction Princess Bibliomuse, Deus-X Krawler, and Pot of the Forbidden. Even so, you don't really get much out of destroying these monsters and sending them to the GY, and besides, the True King you want to play the most of is True King Bahrastos, the Fathomer because of it being able to Special Summon a non-WATER Wyrm monster from Deck if destroyed by card effect. So in order to have some WATER monsters in Deck for a situation where I would need to destroy WATERs to Special Summon Bahrastos, I am playing Deep Sea Diva and Guitar Gurnards Duonigis which also provide a way to get to a Synchro Level 5 to get to Denglong, First of the Yang Zing who can modulate its Level to the Level of a Wyrm monster you send from Deck to GY by its effect. I still really don't recommend playing True King Prediction Princess as an actual Deck option. Because of the varying Attributes of your monsters and the fact that you don't really get much out of destoying your monsters via the True King effects, there is no realistic reason why you should even be considering something like this. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster face-up or face-down and can Special Summon a Flip Monster face-down during the End Phase from hand or GY. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. It can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down and on flip, it can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. This card can Summon itself back face-down if it is Tributed and sent to the GY, and if it is flipped face-up, it can search for a Prediction Princess, other than itself, and a Ritual Spell from Deck. And while it is face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of all monsters on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and it can add a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than itself if it is destroyed on field. 1 Trias Hierarchia which can be sent off of Diviner or Special Summoned off of the effect of World Legacy Monstrosity targeting a True King on the field and Hierarchia can also Tribute a Fairy to Summon itself from hand or GY. For the True Kings: 1 True King Lithosagym, the Disaster, 3 True King Bahrastos, the Fathomer, and 1 Mariamne, the True Dracophoenix. Each True King needs to destroy 2 monsters from hand and/or your field, including at least 1 monster of their respective Attribute, in order to Special Summon themselves from hand. Lithosagym needs EARTH, Bahrastos needs WATER, and Mariamne needs WIND. Each also get an additional effect when you Summon them if you destroy 2 monsters of their required Attribute. Lithosagym allows you to look at your opponent's Extra Deck and banish up to 3 monsters from it with different names. Bahrastos can banish up to 2 Spell/Trap cards from your opponent's field and/or GY. Mariamne can banish up to 4 cards from the top of your opponent's Deck. Each also have an effect that activates if they are destroyed by a card effect: Lithosagym Special Summons a non-EARTH Wyrm monster from GY, Bahrastos Special Summons a non-WATER Wyrm monster from Deck, and Mariamne adds a non-WIND Wyrm monster from Deck to hand. Again, we are playing 3 copies of only Bahrastos because it is the most important one to destroy in order to get itseffect which allows you to Special Summon a non-WATER Wyrm monster from Deck. Say if you destroy Bahrastos and a Deus-X to Special Summon Lithosagym, Lithosagym is 1 Level 9 on field, and the destroyed Bahrastos Special Summons a Mariamne from Deck, giving you your 2nd Level 9 on field to go into a Rank 9. You could play 2 Lithosagym instead of 1 by cutting a copy of Gurnards, but I at least want to guarantee the Diva play in case I draw a Gurnards in my starting hand. Moving on, 2 Guitar Gurnards Duonigis which can banish cards from the top of your opponent's Deck equal to the number of WATER monsters you control if it is Special Summoned. This sets you up for a Deep Sea Prima Donna play, but I am not a fan of that card, so we can just use this effect as a way to scout out what your opponent is playing and maybe even banish an important card from their Deck. It can also target a Level 4 or lower WATER monster you control and increase its Level by its original Level. This goes very well when you get Gurnards off of Diva. By targeting itself, you have material for a Level 8 Synchro to go into White Aura Whale to destroy all Attack Position monsters your opponent controls going second, and if you target Diva, you have material for a Synchro Level 7 to go into Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing which can pop itself and a card your opponent controls going second. And when it's destroyed by battle or a card effect, including by its own effect, you can Special Summon a Wyrm monster from Deck which can get you a True King to set you up for a potential Rank 9 play. 3 Deep Sea Diva which can Special Summon a Level 3 or lower Sea Serpent monster from Deck on Normal Summon. 3 Diviner of the Herald which can send a Fairy monster from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon. And 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Spell/Traps: 1 Dragonic Diagram which can pop a card in hand or your field to add a True King or True Draco card from Deck to hand. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon 1 Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters with a different Type and Attribute than the targeted monster with different names. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 White Aura Whale which needs a Water Tuner and non-Water monsters for material which is easily fulfilled by Diva and Gurnards. On Synchro Summon, it can destroy all Attack Position monsters your opponent controls, and it can declare 2 attacks on your opponent's monsters each Battle Phase, also dealing piercing damage. And if it destroyed by your opponent's card by battle or effect, you can banish another WATER from GY to Special Summon it from GY as a Tuner. 1 Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing which can target a Yang Zing you control and a card your opponent controls and destroy them, and if it is destroyed by battle or card effect and sent to GY, you can Special Summon a Wyrm monster from Deck. 1 Denglong, First of the Yang Zing which can search a Yang ZIng card on Synchro Summon, but we aren't playing anything searchable as nothing is that worthwhile to put in the Deck for Denglong to add, since you aren't always going into Denglong either way. It can also send a Wyrm monster from Deck to GY to change its Level to the Level of the sent monster. You can send a True King to make Denglong a Level 9 for Monstrosity and/or Rank 9 plays. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer, 2 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Kashtira Fenrir, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Solemn Judgment.
